    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's dive into the technical side of the pitot-static system.\n\nThe pitot-static system is a critical component of an aircraft's airspeed indicator. It works by measuring the pressure difference between the air flowing into the pitot tube (from the front of the aircraft) and the static ports (which are usually located on the sides of the aircraft). The pressure difference is caused by the difference in airspeed between the two ports.\n\nIn a typical pitot-static system, the pitot tube is connected to the airspeed indicator, and the static ports are connected to a pressure sensor. The pressure sensor measures the pressure difference between the two ports and sends a signal to the airspeed indicator, which then calculates the aircraft's airspeed based on the pressure difference.\n\nThe airspeed indicator uses a calibrated scale to convert the pressure difference into a corresponding airspeed reading. The scale is typically calibrated to match the actual airspeed of the aircraft at a specific altitude and temperature. If the pitot tube becomes clogged or blocked, the airspeed reading will be inaccurate, as the pressure difference between the two ports will be disrupted.\n\nIn a Cessna 172, the pitot-static system",
      "source": "target",
